ng demands of work and family and the tension between individual rights and social conformity. Using military justice records, Elizabeth Lutes Hillman demonstrates the criminal consequences of the military's violent mission, ideological goals, fear of homosexuality, and attitude toward racial, gender, and class difference. The records also show that only the most inept, unfortunate, and impolitic of misbehaving service members were likely to be prosecuted. Young, poor, low-ranking, and nonwhite servicemen bore a disproportionate burden in the military's enforcement of crime, and gay men and lesbians paid the price for the armed forces' official hostility toward homosexuality. While the U.S. military fought to defend the Constitution, the Cold War court-martial punished those who wavered from accepted political convictions, sexual behavior, and social conventions, threatening the very rights of due process and free expression the Constitution promised.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCold warxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCourts-martial and courts of inquiryxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCourts-martial and courts of inquiryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociology, MilitaryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Military / Wars & Conflicts (Other).2bisacsh  aAberdeen Proving Ground.  aCalifornia.  aCommunist Party.  aCox Commission.  aFerguson, Homer.  aFort Leavenworth.  aFriedan, Betty.  aGesell Committee.  aJonek, Ingrid.  aKismet Café.  aLong Binh jail.  aMann Act.  aNaval Academy.  aWinchell, Barry.  aage demographics.  aall-volunteer force.  abench trials.  ablack market offenses.  acasualties.  acivic organizations.  acivil rights movement.  acoverture.  adesegreg